message:
Shortcut for commenting things out: ctrl + /

Objects are created with { } (vs. arrays which are created by [  ])

var object = { };
objects don't have indexes; they have **key value pairs**. 

keys in objects are always strings but you do not need quotes. You must put a colon after the key, and then you can follow it with other data types separated with commas

var me = {
firstName: 'Alex',
lastName: 'Reisner',
age: 33,
hobbies: ['sleeping', 'kidding', 'crafts'],
pet: {
name: 'Noodle',
hobbies: ['eating', 'biting bees', 'sleeping']
}
};

var name2 = 'firstName';

console.log(me)
console.log(me['firstName']);
console.log(me.firstName);
console.log(me.pet.hobbies[1])
console.log(me[name2]);

Add something to a specific position in an array:

people.splice(1, 3, 'taylor');

Objects are complex data types -- collections. Similar to arrays but do not use indexes.
Use key/value pairs (a pair of a key and a value assigned to that key).
Store any data type in **variables**.
